<br>
Jump-rings are not made one-at-a-time, as you seem to think. What is done, is a length of wire (Also quite easy to make by drawing metal through a 'draw plate') is wrapped around a dowel/rod in a 'spring-like' coil. This long coil of wire is then slid off the rod, and cut down one side, producing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>many</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> rings <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>very</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> fast. Hundreds, if not thousands of jump-rings can be produced this way in a very short amount of time. I have not purchased a single ring for the suit of Chainmail i'm making myself, using this process the entire time. Buying them would just be a waste of money, and only save me a small amount of time.<br>
<br>
A 'commoner' in the past needed no blacksmithing skill to sit down and learn the relitivly easy process of making a piece/suit of Chainmail. Think of it, no TV or radio, no computers, unable to read (Like there was access to the super rare and expensive books), none of the modern leisure activities we waste our time on these days. Time is one thing they had plenty of. Mix in a realm at war and in need of more troops with the best armor they can manage to make, and nothing but time to make it, and you have many suits of Chainmail being produced.<br>
<br>
Blacksmith's time was far to valuable to be spent on this work that didn't need their skills, since it took many years (Of a much shorter life-span) of appenticeship to learn these skills. The time it takes to 'weave' them is still not nearly as intensive compaired to the time it takes to heat an entire piece of raw metal, and pound it with thousands of blows into a desired shape. Progress on the weave is actually quite amazing one you get into the groove, and all the fitting and size tweaking can be done mostly after the Chainmail is almosy done. The Platemail requires constant tweaking and ajusting as an on-going process for it to fit the final user. If Platemail was so much easier (and considered so much better in protection) to produce, why weren't more then the elite/royal troops out-fitted in it? Why were the British royal family out-fitted in Spanish made armor from so far away? Becuase it was only there that the level of skill could be found to produce Platemail to their standards. Trust me, smithing is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>very</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> time consuming, on top of the years-and-years of learning needed to get really good at it. Even i'm only a modestly skilled smith, with many years of practice and learning still ahead of me to become what i'd consider a 'master'.<br>
<br>
And, as i final note, if a Blacksmith <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>were</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to take their valuable time to make a suit of Chainmail he would have out-sourced the repetitive work of making large secions of of the Mail to apprentices and commoners, only to do the final fitting and assembly work personally. There were plenty of people with the time to sit and do the work.<br>
<br>
When <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>all</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the factors are put into consideration; the cost to produce heat (You gotta chop down the wood, drag it back, stoke the forge, over-and-over. There's no natural gas that's 'always on'), the time it takes to actually fit and smith out a piece of armor, the avalibility of ore that is of high enough quality to actually make platemale, and the limited number of people who actually have the long-learned skills needed to make a piece of Platemail, the cost/value of Platemail goes through the roof compaired to Chainmail. Time is a major factor, but only one piece of the big puzzle. And i still have to argue that smithing out a large piece of armor is going to be just as time consuming as producing a large piece of Chainmail, on top of the other costs. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#c0c0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/blighttanksofdaoc.showUserPublicProfile?gid=xainder>Xainder</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 76<br> <font color=#000000>(6/22/03 11:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/flighttanksofdaocfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=62.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Comparison</span><hr size=1> Oh, and as Raven said, that is exactly why Minstrels get Evade 2. They lack alot of the offesive punch and the Hits that we Merc's get.<br>
