<br>
See, I have a friend who's horny over that stuff.  His dream is to have a forge and make swords and armor.  He's a geek when it comes to the tecnicalities of metals, their properties, how to temper them, forge them, how to make it.  He's done all the reasearch he can, right down to a business plan and what kind of market he could sell too.  So he's the guy that you're basically arguing with.  Here's what he says.<br>
<br>
Chain Mail made from wire is nice for decoration.  True, it's easy to make, and cheap.  It's probably the most common form of chain mail present today in &quot;live action roleplaying&quot; because of this.  However, he wouldn't wear one of those to save his life.    <br>
<br>
Take a square of chain mail made this way, go to a lumber yard, and tack the square to a piece of firewood.  Stand the firewood on end with the mail facing to a side, then take a swipe at the mail with an axe, hard enough to make the firewood go fly a few feet (if the axe doesn't stick in the wood).  Then, have fun picking out your wire links from the wood.<br>
<br>
The kind of mail that someone would pay for and wear  (because it's more flexible/breathable than Plate) to protect their life would be made from something much &quot;harder&quot; than some wire you can manually wrap around a rod and cut.<br>
<br>
<br>
I'm not going to comment any further, because you two are probably going to get technical on me and I don't really care.  I posted this much just to defend my original claim since I did stick my nose into this.<br>
<br>
But there is one thing I know from reading.  Many European royal families used to seek out Spanish made swords (Damascus?  I'm not sure if this is the city) because the metal was a better quality, as well as the methods of making the sword.  It turns out that the ore they were getting had many imperfections (carbon) in it, which resulted in a better quality alloy at the end of the making of the sword.  I know, swords aren't armor.  But I'll make this correlation.  If the ore used for making swords was better, wouldn't the ore be as good for making armor??  <br>
<br>
When that particular source of ore was depleted, or became purer, whatever...Damascus? had established itself as a center for swordmaking such that the masters of the trade flocked there.  There wasn't THAT much more knowledge in Damascus than anywhere else, it's just that their supply of Ore happened to be better before they ever knew that the ore was that important.<br>
<br>
What I'm saying is, the fact that the royal family got their Plate Mail armor from Spain, in my mind, has nothing to do with the tradeoff in difficulty between making chain and plate armor.  <br>
<br>
And umm, unless someone can prove Richard Cohen wrong (the author of the book I'm getting this all from), there was no &quot;Chain Mail&quot; in that era, so once again, what difference does it make where the Royal family got their armor? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#ffffff><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/blighttanksofdaoc.showUserPublicProfile?gid=blame@lighttanksofdaoc>Blame</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://homepages.internet.lu/lordoftherings/images/boromir.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Determined Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 447<br> <font color=#000000>(6/25/03 2:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/flighttanksofdaocfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=62.topic&index=47>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Spanish steel - much stronger than our native blade</span><hr size=1> I would always prefer to buy weapons and armour from Spaniards anyway. Living on the European servers, I can say those crazy foreigners are muchas better company than a lot of people who have a 'full' grasp of the English language.<br>
